AUDIENCE: And the next
question is for you Jon.

00:35:48.270 --> 00:35:51.775
Being that your character
uses such military precision,

00:35:51.775 --> 00:35:53.150
can you tell us
a little bit more

00:35:53.150 --> 00:35:55.816
about what you did to
prepare for the role?

00:36:02.740 --> 00:36:05.440
JON BERNTHAL: I mean as far as
the physicality and the weapons

00:36:05.440 --> 00:36:10.636
training, I think when
you prepare for a part,

00:36:10.636 --> 00:36:11.489
it's twofold, right?

00:36:11.489 --> 00:36:12.780
There's all the physical stuff.

00:36:12.780 --> 00:36:14.140
There's how is he going to walk?

00:36:14.140 --> 00:36:15.139
How is he going to talk?

00:36:15.139 --> 00:36:19.840
How is he going to handle the
familiarity with the props,

00:36:19.840 --> 00:36:22.880
the weapons, and
so on and so forth?

00:36:22.880 --> 00:36:25.710
But then there's the
real deal preparation.

00:36:25.710 --> 00:36:28.500
And that's the diving
in, the emotional stuff.

00:36:28.500 --> 00:36:34.850
And I've said before, I'm
a husband and I'm a father.

00:36:34.850 --> 00:36:36.760
And I think that
there's no way I

00:36:36.760 --> 00:36:41.440
could begin to even attempt
to tackle this part until I

00:36:41.440 --> 00:36:42.510
got there.

00:36:42.510 --> 00:36:46.950
I think until I really
realized and know

00:36:46.950 --> 00:36:50.250
in my bones what it's like to
love people so much more than I

00:36:50.250 --> 00:36:53.860
love myself and so willingly
would give up my life for them,

00:36:53.860 --> 00:36:57.080
how can I begin to imagine what
it would be like for this man

00:36:57.080 --> 00:37:00.210
if somebody took his family?

00:37:00.210 --> 00:37:02.590
And what that
requires, for me, is

00:37:02.590 --> 00:37:09.080
going to a really, really scary,
really, really dark place.

00:37:09.080 --> 00:37:11.610
And since it scared the living
shit out of me, I was like,

00:37:11.610 --> 00:37:12.670
I really got to do this.

00:37:12.670 --> 00:37:15.480
I really got to try this.

00:37:15.480 --> 00:37:20.472
But that's where it kind of all
sort of starts with me is that.

00:37:20.472 --> 00:37:22.180
Sorry, that doesn't
answer your question,

00:37:22.180 --> 00:37:23.179
but that's where-- yeah.

00:37:23.179 --> 00:37:24.454
Sorry.

00:37:24.454 --> 00:37:25.620
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

00:37:25.620 --> 00:37:27.429
KEVIN VLK: Last question.

00:37:27.429 --> 00:37:28.220
AUDIENCE: Hey guys.

00:37:28.220 --> 00:37:29.203
Thank you for coming along.

00:37:29.203 --> 00:37:31.550
It's been a pleasure seeing
you guys answer questions

00:37:31.550 --> 00:37:32.800
and discuss them.

00:37:32.800 --> 00:37:37.227
One question for
you Karen is, being

00:37:37.227 --> 00:37:41.305
in the middle from the
perspective of seeing Daredevil

00:37:41.305 --> 00:37:44.246
do what he does in
helping out the community,

00:37:44.246 --> 00:37:47.630
but also in season two
seeing Punisher kind of exact

00:37:47.630 --> 00:37:49.810
his revenge of what the
normal citizen would

00:37:49.810 --> 00:37:52.410
want if he was in that
predicament of losing someone,

00:37:52.410 --> 00:37:55.320
how do you feel her
character interprets

00:37:55.320 --> 00:37:57.087
the right moral
choice as [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:57.087 --> 00:37:58.420
CHARLIE COX: Oh, great question.

00:37:58.420 --> 00:38:01.270
DEBORAH ANN WOLL: I mean, you've
hit upon Karen's storyline

00:38:01.270 --> 00:38:03.844
for season two, essentially.

00:38:03.844 --> 00:38:05.260
I think if you
look at someone who

00:38:05.260 --> 00:38:06.843
has this questionable
past-- we're not

00:38:06.843 --> 00:38:08.860
quite sure what
that is, but we do

00:38:08.860 --> 00:38:10.630
know about what
happened with Wesley.

00:38:10.630 --> 00:38:13.520
Now if the whole world looks
at Frank Castle and says,

00:38:13.520 --> 00:38:16.539
he's a monster, then
Karen's a monster.

00:38:16.539 --> 00:38:18.080
If the whole world
looks at Daredevil

00:38:18.080 --> 00:38:21.690
and says Daredevil's a hero,
well, Karen took it too far.

00:38:21.690 --> 00:38:24.770
So I think she looks at
these examples of people

00:38:24.770 --> 00:38:26.560
who are doing
things in her life,

00:38:26.560 --> 00:38:29.390
and she has to determine
for herself whether she

00:38:29.390 --> 00:38:33.070
thinks what she did was right.

00:38:33.070 --> 00:38:36.412
And it's an
unanswerable question.

00:38:36.412 --> 00:38:37.870
I mean, there is
no answer to that.

00:38:37.870 --> 00:38:39.670
It's not right,
and it's not wrong.

00:38:39.670 --> 00:38:45.650
And she was in a situation that
none of us-- we hope none of us

00:38:45.650 --> 00:38:47.900
will ever be in.

00:38:47.900 --> 00:38:51.480
So I think I can go so far to
say that Karen is fascinated

00:38:51.480 --> 00:38:54.610
by Frank Castle and what he
means, what he represents,

00:38:54.610 --> 00:38:57.170
because in some ways
he represents her.

00:38:57.170 --> 00:38:58.400
AUDIENCE: Thank so much.

00:38:58.400 --> 00:38:58.790
KEVIN VLK: Thank you.

00:38:58.790 --> 00:38:59.430
Great question.

00:38:59.430 --> 00:39:00.929
And quickly, because
I know you guys

00:39:00.929 --> 00:39:04.170
got to go, just through your
guys' development from season

00:39:04.170 --> 00:39:06.830
one now to season two, and now
you guys joining on season two,

00:39:06.830 --> 00:39:10.160
just from the beginning
of that to the end, what

00:39:10.160 --> 00:39:12.950
did you find in your characters
that surprised you the most

00:39:12.950 --> 00:39:15.408
or that excited you the most
about each of your characters?

00:39:17.419 --> 00:39:18.710
ELODIE YUNG: You looking at me?

00:39:18.710 --> 00:39:20.210
KEVIN VLK: I'm
looking right at you.

00:39:20.210 --> 00:39:22.256
You haven't spoken in a while.

00:39:22.256 --> 00:39:24.880
ELODIE YUNG: I don't think there
is one thing I could pick from

00:39:24.880 --> 00:39:29.200
this character that
really [NON-ENGLISH]--

00:39:29.200 --> 00:39:32.780
stands out more for me.

00:39:32.780 --> 00:39:35.880
It's not English,
but you guys got it.

00:39:35.880 --> 00:39:39.900
You know, Elektra is
such a complex character.

00:39:39.900 --> 00:39:41.570
For me, just having
the opportunity

00:39:41.570 --> 00:39:48.660
to get to know what-- just go
back to the essence of Elektra

00:39:48.660 --> 00:39:51.250
and discover this
world of comics

00:39:51.250 --> 00:39:54.080
was something new and
fascinating for me.

00:39:54.080 --> 00:39:59.170
Trying to capture the essence
and put it in this character

00:39:59.170 --> 00:40:03.685
that we built for the
show was exciting.

00:40:07.180 --> 00:40:09.590
I talked a lot with
the writers, and they

00:40:09.590 --> 00:40:11.260
wanted her to be a sociopath.

00:40:11.260 --> 00:40:14.650
So I had to do some
homework and really

00:40:14.650 --> 00:40:19.490
trying to find out
what a sociopath is.

00:40:19.490 --> 00:40:23.630
Yeah, playing someone that
seemed to be very cold,

00:40:23.630 --> 00:40:30.500
that has no remorse, no sense
of guilt, no sense of empathy

00:40:30.500 --> 00:40:33.940
or who doesn't care about
the well-being of others,

00:40:33.940 --> 00:40:36.910
that was something actually
pretty interesting for me.

00:40:36.910 --> 00:40:40.040
All this aspect, all this
side was really good.

00:40:40.040 --> 00:40:45.670
But then tapping into my own
emotions and my own experience

00:40:45.670 --> 00:40:54.560
to bring some of her more human
side and some of this failure

00:40:54.560 --> 00:40:58.810
that I talked about with this
relationship and this love

00:40:58.810 --> 00:41:01.810
she had once for
Matthew, that was also

00:41:01.810 --> 00:41:06.770
very-- that was great
as an actress to do that

00:41:06.770 --> 00:41:08.490
as well, in some scenes.

00:41:08.490 --> 00:41:10.550
So the whole thing.

00:41:10.550 --> 00:41:13.480
I mean, I just love
Elektra, and that's it.

00:41:13.480 --> 00:41:15.060
It was just good for me.

00:41:15.060 --> 00:41:17.477
It was really good.

00:41:17.477 --> 00:41:18.810
JON BERNTHAL: What surprised me?

00:41:21.446 --> 00:41:32.070
I think that he's in
such a dark sort of cloud

00:41:32.070 --> 00:41:36.630
of rage and anger, but
within that, his ability

00:41:36.630 --> 00:41:41.910
to be not just tactical
in terms of how he fights,

00:41:41.910 --> 00:41:44.130
but psychologically tactical.

00:41:44.130 --> 00:41:47.090
And he's got the
ability to manipulate.

00:41:47.090 --> 00:41:48.060
And he can be cunning.

00:41:48.060 --> 00:41:53.690
And that was a pleasant surprise
that they let me kind of play

00:41:53.690 --> 00:41:56.774
with that, I guess
his intelligence.

00:41:56.774 --> 00:41:58.440
DEBORAH ANN WOLL: I
won't cry this time.

00:42:01.290 --> 00:42:08.450
I, Deborah, am sort of a
silly, dare I say dorky person.

00:42:08.450 --> 00:42:11.312
And I never really saw
much room for that in Karen

00:42:11.312 --> 00:42:12.020
at the beginning.

00:42:12.020 --> 00:42:13.510
She seemed like
such a serious sort

00:42:13.510 --> 00:42:15.080
of intelligent minded person.

00:42:15.080 --> 00:42:16.730
And this year I
think I was surprised

00:42:16.730 --> 00:42:19.550
I was able to find more
of that aspect of myself

00:42:19.550 --> 00:42:22.260
in it, that there
were moments where

00:42:22.260 --> 00:42:24.000
she felt a little awkward.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.375
I feel like she cannot keep
her cool around Matt Murdock.

00:42:26.375 --> 00:42:30.084
And there are some
really fun moments

00:42:30.084 --> 00:42:31.750
that I can't talk
about too specifically

00:42:31.750 --> 00:42:34.750
where serious, serious
things were happening.

00:42:34.750 --> 00:42:37.490
And then we did a
scene following it,

00:42:37.490 --> 00:42:41.170
and there were moments where
I found myself cracking jokes

00:42:41.170 --> 00:42:43.320
that I didn't even know
were in the script,

00:42:43.320 --> 00:42:45.430
and sort of laughing in them.

00:42:45.430 --> 00:42:50.390
And I don't know, it was a
surprising, cool thing to find.

00:42:50.390 --> 00:42:51.940
CHARLIE COX: A
really good question.

00:42:51.940 --> 00:42:55.000
The thing that sprung to
mind was that, I guess,

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:57.170
what surprised me
about the character,

00:42:57.170 --> 00:42:59.996
but also I think about all
characters, all people,

00:42:59.996 --> 00:43:01.870
is that we're kind of
walking contradictions,

00:43:01.870 --> 00:43:04.960
you know, and we can
simultaneously believe

00:43:04.960 --> 00:43:08.560
two very, very opposite things.

00:43:08.560 --> 00:43:11.060
I think it's a Kris
Kristofferson song where

00:43:11.060 --> 00:43:13.870
he says we're walking
contradictions

00:43:13.870 --> 00:43:16.420
or something like those things.

00:43:16.420 --> 00:43:18.890
And I think with
Matt that's probably

00:43:18.890 --> 00:43:26.340
the thing that confuses
the most is that he's

00:43:26.340 --> 00:43:27.830
one person with Karen.

00:43:27.830 --> 00:43:29.242
And that is very true.

00:43:29.242 --> 00:43:30.200
That is very authentic.

00:43:30.200 --> 00:43:32.574
That is really how he believes
and what he wants in life.

00:43:32.574 --> 00:43:35.300
And then he's a very
different person with Elektra.

00:43:35.300 --> 00:43:38.430
That side of himself is
also valid, is also real.

00:43:38.430 --> 00:43:42.080
And yet if, as an
outsider, if you

00:43:42.080 --> 00:43:43.872
were to see those
behaviors, you would say,

00:43:43.872 --> 00:43:44.830
that guy's a hypocrite.

00:43:44.830 --> 00:43:46.340
But I'm not sure
that that's true.

00:43:46.340 --> 00:43:49.712
And I think often we relate to
those kind of things as people.

00:43:49.712 --> 00:43:50.420
KEVIN VLK: Great.

00:43:50.420 --> 00:43:52.440
Well thank you guys so
much for being here.

00:43:52.440 --> 00:43:54.790
CHARLIE COX: Thanks
so much guys.

